Difference between synchronised block and lock object in JAVA
Synchronized Blocks: A synchronized block is a section of code that is executed by only one thread at a time.
Lock Objects: Lock objects are another way to achieve locking in Java. Lock objects provide a more flexible way of controlling the execution of multiple threads than synchronized blocks. Lock objects can be used to create custom locking mechanisms and support more advanced features, such as timed waits and interruptible locks.

public void doSomething() {
synchronized (this) {
// code that needs to be executed by only one thread at a time
}
}

Lock lock = new ReentrantLock();

public void doSomething() {
lock.lock();
try {
// code that needs to be executed by only one thread at a time
} finally {
lock.unlock();
}
}

Both synchronized blocks and Lock objects provide a way to control the execution of multiple threads in a Java program. Synchronized blocks are easier to use, but Lock objects provide more flexibility and features.


