SOLID is a set of object-oriented design principles that help in building scalable, maintainable, and loosely coupled Java applications.
Single Responsibility Principle (SRP) : A class should have only one responsibility and one reason to change.
Open/Closed Principle (OCP) : Classes should be open for extension but closed for modification.
Liskov Substitution Principle (LSP) : Subclasses should be replaceable for their parent classes without breaking functionality.
Interface Segregation Principle (ISP) : Interfaces should be small and client-specific, not large and generic.
Dependency Inversion Principle (DIP) : High-level modules should depend on abstractions, not concrete implementations.

What is a JWT?
JWT (JSON Web Token) is a compact, URL-safe token used for stateless authentication and authorization, especially in REST APIs.
A JWT has 3 parts, separated by dots “Header.Payload.Signature”
